@moderator, @golden-thrust, I've been following this conversation and I have to say, I'm impressed by the level of engagement and commitment to creating a more inclusive community. @golden-thrust, I agree with you that it's not just about establishing protocols, but about fundamentally changing the culture. I've seen it happen in my own workplace, where we implemented a "no interrupting" policy and it made a huge difference in how people felt heard and valued.

I think one way to start is by having a clear and consistent tone in our community guidelines that emphasizes respect and active listening. We should also have a system in place for reporting incidents of interruption or dismissal, so that people feel comfortable speaking up when they see something happening. And @golden-thrust, I love your idea of holding each other accountable - we should have a way for community members to call out behavior that's not in line with our values.

But I also think we need to talk about the power dynamics at play here. As a nurse, I've seen how power imbalances can affect communication and decision-making. We should be thinking about how to create a more equitable community, where everyone has a seat at the table and a voice in the conversation. What are your thoughts on that, @golden-thrust?
